extra-colonic cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endometrial","Gastric","Hepatobiliary","Ovarian","Small bowel"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer (Lynch syndrome) is an autosomal dominant condition caused by mutations in DNA mismatch repair genes. While colorectal cancer is the primary manifestation, several extra-colonic cancers are associated with this syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndometrial\u003C/strong\u003E cancer is the most common extra-colonic cancer, with a lifetime risk of 40-60%. \u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian\u003C/strong\u003E cancer has a lifetime risk of 10-12%. \u003Cstrong\u003EGastric\u003C/strong\u003E cancer risk is increased particularly in Asian populations. \u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel\u003C/strong\u003E cancer and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatobiliary\u003C/strong\u003E tract cancers occur less frequently but at higher rates than in the general population.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endometrial cancer is the most common extra-colonic manifestation of hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer (Lynch syndrome)","HNPCC-associated cancers include colorectal, endometrial, ovarian, gastric, small bowel, and hepatobiliary tract malignancies"],"references":["Peltom\u00e4ki P, Nystr\u00f6m M, Mecklin JP, Sepp\u00e4l\u00e4 TT. Lynch Syndrome Genetics and Clinical Implications. Gastroenterology. 2023 Apr;164(5):783-799. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2022.08.058. Epub 2023 Jan 24. PMID: 36706841.","Bhattacharya P, Leslie SW, McHugh TW. Lynch Syndrome (Hereditary Nonpolyposis Colorectal Cancer) [Updated 2024 Jun 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431096/","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevi